:::summary
The Scientific Revolution (c. 1543–1687) was the transformation of humanity's understanding of nature that overturned the ancient Ptolemaic-Aristotelian worldview and established the methods and principles of modern science. Beginning with Copernicus's heliocentric hypothesis (1543) and culminating in Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687), it was one of the most profound intellectual revolutions in human history — one that reshaped how educated people understood not only the physical world but humanity's place within it.
:::

